So they show that their average reward in these games is kind of noisy, but it improves over time, especially also if you look at the average Q of the max action, it continuously goes up during training.

00:20.467 --> 00:32.906
So this is really a successful training, especially this investigative experiment they did right here, where you can see one example of how the Q function, what the Q function says.

00:32.966 --> 00:40.358
Remember, the Q function gives us the, whatever the future reward is going to be.

00:40.819 --> 00:41.099
Okay.

00:41.319 --> 00:43.723
And here we always look at the max action.

00:43.703 --> 00:49.252
So in this first frame, you can see this enemy had just appeared.

00:50.053 --> 00:55.862
And you can see that from here to here, there's a spike in the queue value because you can shoot enemies.

00:56.583 --> 00:58.846
And that gives you reward.

00:59.327 --> 01:12.327
The A, this is already, so the enemy isn't shot yet by the simple appearance of the enemy, the queue function also like already jumps in value because it anticipates a future reward.

01:12.307 --> 01:21.283
Then the agent shoots, and you can see here the shot is about to land at the enemy, and that's when we're here.

01:21.383 --> 01:26.893
So this, now the Q function is very sure that in the future there's going to be a high reward.

01:27.574 --> 01:31.902
But then once the enemy is shot,

01:31.882 --> 01:34.526
then there is no more enemy to be shot.

01:35.408 --> 01:48.068
And the Q function drops drastically because it doesn't see a future reward as being as likely as at the beginning when there was this new enemy to be shot.

01:48.088 --> 01:50.071
So that's, you know, pretty interesting.

01:50.091 --> 01:57.703
And you can see pretty directly that there is a correlation between what's happening in the game and this learned Q function.

02:00.569 --> 02:20.258
If you compare this to other methods and they really say that these other methods, most of them have some kind of very special feature engineered, like, so their method just takes RGB, but the other methods recognize that, oh, in these Atari games, most of the time, you know, there are unique colors for the things.

02:20.519 --> 02:30.053
So, you know, the enemies are all like green, like, and they make unique channels for those green enemies, or they even have handcrafted object detectors.

02:30.033 --> 02:32.838
and tell the algorithm where these objects are.

02:33.379 --> 02:42.035
So the comparison really isn't fair, yet the DQN outperformed these others like almost everywhere.

